posts.title: Reshaping the Administrative State: The End of Chevron Deference and Trump's SES Overhaul
posts.content:
The Supreme Court’s decision to overturn Chevron deference, combined with Trump’s executive order to restructure the Senior Executive Service (SES), represents one of the most significant shifts in government accountability in modern history. This one-two punch directly confronts the unchecked power of the administrative state, ensuring that unelected bureaucrats no longer have the final say in shaping policy that affects millions of Americans.

Ending Chevron: Restoring the Separation of Powers For 40 years, Chevron U.S.A., Inc. v. Natural Resources Defense Council (1984) allowed federal agencies to interpret ambiguous laws in whatever way they saw fit, so long as their interpretation was “reasonable.” This effectively let unelected bureaucrats—not Congress or the courts—define and enforce laws, giving regulatory agencies massive, unchecked power over everything from environmental policy to business regulations.

By overturning Chevron, the Supreme Court has:

Put Power Back in the Hands of Judges – Courts will now determine the correct interpretation of laws instead of deferring to agency interpretations. This means agencies can no longer twist laws to expand their authority. Reined in Regulatory Overreach – Agencies like the EPA, FDA, and IRS have used Chevron deference to push sweeping rules that were never explicitly authorized by Congress. Without Chevron, their ability to impose broad regulations is severely weakened. Restored Legislative Accountability – Congress can no longer pass vague laws and expect agencies to fill in the gaps. Lawmakers will be forced to write clearer, more precise legislation—bringing lawmaking back to elected representatives rather than unelected bureaucrats. Trump’s SES Overhaul: Draining the Bureaucratic Swamp While ending Chevron takes power away from agencies, Trump’s plan to restructure the Senior Executive Service (SES) would take direct aim at the people within them—the career bureaucrats who have long been shielded from accountability.

What Is the SES? The SES consists of high-level federal employees who manage and implement agency policies. They are supposed to be nonpartisan professionals, but in reality, many are entrenched bureaucrats who wield enormous influence, often undermining elected leadership. The Problem: These bureaucrats are incredibly difficult to fire. Even when they actively obstruct an administration’s policies, they remain in place, ensuring that the government operates as a self-sustaining machine rather than as a reflection of the people’s will. Trump’s Solution: Schedule F – Trump’s executive order would reclassify tens of thousands of federal employees as “Schedule F,” making them at-will employees who can be fired if they resist implementing an administration’s policies. This means: No More Permanent Deep State – Presidents would be able to clean house, replacing obstructionist bureaucrats with those who actually follow the administration’s agenda. Government That Works for the People – Instead of agencies resisting elected leadership, they would be staffed with individuals who carry out the policies voters chose. Why This Is a Huge Win for the American People Restoring Accountability – No more hidden government. Congress writes the laws, the courts interpret them, and the executive branch enforces them—exactly as the Founders intended. Boosting Economic Growth – Without overreaching regulations strangling businesses, companies will have more freedom to innovate, grow, and create jobs. Protecting Individual Liberties – Agencies like the ATF and FDA have used Chevron to push controversial policies without Congressional approval. Now, their power is limited, protecting Americans from excessive government control. Eliminating Bureaucratic Resistance – When voters elect a president, they expect policy changes. Under the current system, career bureaucrats can slow-walk or outright sabotage those changes. Trump’s reforms ensure the executive branch actually follows the president’s directives. Reducing Government Bloat – Fewer bureaucrats with unchecked power mean a leaner, more efficient government. Less red tape, fewer redundant regulations, and more responsiveness to the people. A New Era of Limited Government Together, the end of Chevron deference and Trump’s SES overhaul mark a historic shift in power—away from unelected bureaucrats and back toward the people and their elected representatives. This isn’t just a policy win; it’s a fundamental restoration of constitutional government. It ensures that laws are made by lawmakers, interpreted by judges, and enforced by the executive branch—not by lifelong bureaucrats who answer to no one.

For decades, the administrative state has acted as a shadow government, growing in power regardless of which party was in charge. These reforms break that cycle, ensuring that government once again serves the people, rather than the other way around.
